yet tomorrow, but the sky falls asleep. Cinder is the crunch in the leaves, and with my eyes, I funnel maple into your veins. You become the middle of my heart, my voice.</p><p>The hillside is chained by a glowing orange moon. We ready our bodies for <i>staying</i>, one of the heaviest acts in the world. So we are the heavy rocks carried with this sky as it falls. It is the letting go&ndash;letting go of our hands&ndash;that is the most important part of staying.</p><p>The night doesn&rsquo;t forget our old movements. We were so fast and now we are finally still. Your car breathes, a lung in the sleepy lights. We watch from the inside, sprayed gently by the reach of nightwash, and I love you in this light as we chase the constellations.</p><p>It&rsquo;s coming for us. It must be.</p><p><b><i>ii.</i></b><br>My blood is<br>the baritone, the perspiring<br>heat, and the engine<br>rumble in me.<br>My blood is half<br>asleep. Its favorite song should<br>drone, should resound<br>in the sky.</p><p>I want it<br>through the open<br>window.<br>I&rsquo;ll let it pierce on. I love<br>my blood&rsquo;s<br>sadness it gifted<br>me: to grow beside<br>love.<br>See my blood sprawled on<br>a small bed,<br>maybe not sleeping<br>much at all.</p><p>How many<br>nights now<br>does it drown in<br>its dreams?</p><p>I&rsquo;ll take my blood&rsquo;s hand to<br>the river.<br>I&rsquo;ll teach it to swim far, <br>far away. I&rsquo;ll laugh<br>when it laughs. I&rsquo;ll cry<br>harder. We&rsquo;re terrifying,<br>not-stopping, radiant<br>sharp sounds<br>dropped in blue<br>light.</p><p>Where you stand<br>on this shore is<br>never enough,<br>sometimes too much.<br>To swim your way<br>back<br>and forth is real<br>love, is<br>the love blood<br>loves.</p><p><b><i>iii.</i></b><br>When I&rsquo;m back home, it&rsquo;s
with two lives inside me&ndash; just as it&rsquo;s always been. It happens almost
immediately. I summon yellow evening like a sponge in my front yard. Lost time
settles back into my pores and in comes the quiet. Wait is only a word; this is
different; this is the pour&nbsp;of an empty sky wrung of day&rsquo;s fire.</p><p>So I dream to an old
soft lullaby. My prayers snap in the old roast of my burning. Coals choke on
the spilled glint of my sad. I&rsquo;m lost, very lost in this body; I need the words
so I can come back. Delana, won&rsquo;t you tell me you&rsquo;ll be the one that doesn&rsquo;t go
away? There&rsquo;s little sleep in my quiet, but I swear all my verses are yours.
I&rsquo;m not always a boy become an island.</p><p>And at midnight, call
my name when you wake. I&rsquo;ll be there in your sleeping brightness, calmness,
uncovering; I&rsquo;ll be your verbal promise that it&rsquo;s more than forever. Here is
the familiar:&nbsp;the heel catching in the soil, the eyes
lost in the sky, and the right hand holding the sun. Delana, you make sound&ndash;
you make me&ndash; come back to the okay.&nbsp;I&rsquo;m driving to you, driving to you
now.<br></p><p><b><i>iv.</i></b><br>I&rsquo;m thankful for the
constant sunburst, the curious and the mellow in me, the same waiting that leaves room to
learn, and Delana&rsquo;s love. I&rsquo;m happy in my family, in love, and in health&ndash; and
there is more to that than one should ever take for granted. I eat the moon from the sky as though a peach from a tree, with eyes dancing to the dance of bird flocks, and write it all down to remember. I&rsquo;m new every morning, new every night, but to stay is the truest gift. To stay where she sleeps, to be where she wakes. To stay a mother&rsquo;s son, to accept a father&rsquo;s love. To stay a brother and speak friendship to the roaming and lost. These honors recreate the story of my beating heart. More than forever, I promise to stay.<br></p>
						
