                    <div class="text post">
	
                        
                            <h2>While You Bathe Our Home in Candlelight</h2>
                        

                        <p>&ldquo;Keep,&rdquo; the warped bell tolls in
the land where no train tracks sing. October is over and I&rsquo;m a red leaf falling.
Summer has shimmered away, has done its shimmering, and what&rsquo;s dead is dead&mdash;for
now. All across the soot-sullied plain dawns the great ashen plumes, tuck me in their
blankets, kiss me goodnight. And there&rsquo;s a chorus of eyelids pulsing a dream:
<i>heaven is nothing but below our feet</i>.</p><p>If there are many tomorrows after the next one, I hope they contain silences&ndash;silences long enough for my eyes to adjust to the dancing light, and know a god whose eyelids pulse too, like frail
butterflies while she dreams. I remember a morning I woke and Delana drove me
into the mountains where stars swept our spirits into the current of a simultaneous
cascade, earth and sky coalescing, a swarm of little wishes and hazel light. I looked
at her in the front seat of her car and time stopped.</p><p>I
believe I am the forever&rsquo;s I speak. As the turnstile of my heart registers my melancholy, I still
speak. A resonant tone must keep, driving my heart onward. &ldquo;Forever,&rdquo; in a city where the palest buildings turn purple come the evening&rsquo;s limbs, collapsing, hugging the bark of my being. I wake in forever,
walk its course under red leaves, falling but alive, aware. Willows sing on
the inside; birds make their nests and clog the sky&rsquo;s veins. I&rsquo;m a red leaf falling, an echo
rewound, but I want to love forever. I know I can love <i>forever.</i></p><p>I&rsquo;m
going to take her back to my home. Catch the train track&rsquo;s song. It sounds
like mine. I want to sleep with her in the same bed I dreamed of her&mdash;before
her. I want to tell her forever. And if the future comes, I want harps playing
while we melt into the shiver, asleep in the greyscale of dull earth&rsquo;s November
and its scattered stars. I&rsquo;ve imagined my death but only to remember what&rsquo;s
most important, Delana. Sleep with me this month under the moon and tell me it&rsquo;s
good.<i> Heaven is nothing but below our feet</i>. And I will write every night, every
night, to feel it&rsquo;s real.</p>
						
