                    <div class="text post">
	
                        
                            <h2>My Solitude Asleep in Yellow</h2>
                        

                        <p>I can almost smell firewood burn. I can almost hear the wind
laugh. It&rsquo;s been a year since the leaves were carmine, firebrick, and burgundy;
branches faced whatever sunlight that shined. Acorns slept in the gutters
between cigarette butts and soot, and all the streetlights loomed like owls.
Each morning would pursue an echo that roused blackness between stars. <i>I want to go, go far, far away</i>. So long
ago words felt like they could change me, and once spoken into the air, they
turned back to me weeping like I had abandoned them. I always felt sorry for the
little things I spoke. And what did I pray for when I slept alone? Delana, I
would reread the letter you gave me before I left DC. I didn&rsquo;t know I was in
love with something else.</p><p>In the mornings, I walked into my backyard and confused my disease
with indica strains and the sprawling canopy light, let my body rouse the
island&rsquo;s silence to a message I needed to hear. &ldquo;Stop,&rdquo; it shouted. &ldquo;Just be.
Just let yourself be.&rdquo; My heart raced at the voice, not yet the words.</p><p>Then I crossed state lines and made my home near you. Your hair
shorter, like the days. We were like the night. The scents of timber and
mountain air tongued like lovers, where starlets fell on Connecticut Avenue,
whispering &ldquo;Just be. Just let yourself be.&rdquo; Imagine feeling the river drink
your skin. I&rsquo;m not the wall to your voice. You&rsquo;re not a mystery unfolding. I&rsquo;ve
come to live in the sounds of your life like a song I&rsquo;ve cried to, a song I&rsquo;ve
prayed to. I drank beside you with the snow falling. With the blonde breath soaking
through thin blinds, and the murmurs of our friends surrounding, three throbs rang
in my throat of<i> will you let me sleep
beside you</i>?</p><p>My spine is built of fire and stone, and I yell come home
blue sky over a ragged heart. It races. It races. It speaks, <i>be, </i>just<i> be</i>. And when I try, I let my frail soul collapse out of me, to drain
like shower water into your birthmarks. And become lost to your youth&mdash;a year&rsquo;s
drift inside one another, to chase a current that goes on and on and on (and on
and on and on and on). The walls of the world inside you fossilized in amber
and cocoa, all tunneling toward, tunneling toward&hellip;</p><p>Always words like always. It feels like always. Our years tangled like
lines on a map. Delana, with your hair everywhere and in my hands before sleep,
dream New Jersey and ocean waves, outstretched hands, and reread letters. While
the wind laughs in a whisper, bright and long the streetlight&rsquo;s loom; while September
smells like firewood burning; I&rsquo;ll hold you always and know my home.</p>
						
						<div class="postmeta"><a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/151087787967/my-solitude-asleep-in-yellow">2 months ago</a>&nbsp; <a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/151087787967/my-solitude-asleep-in-yellow" style="text-transform:lowercase;">Notes (2)</a></div>

