                    <div class="text post">
	
                        
                            <h2>Salt Over the Brine</h2>
                        

                        <p>Will my goodness spoil with the sun as it falls during its course? Has each day passed sufficiently into the past forever, where my eyes can never reach? When will the time come that my heart unwinds entirely, all to begin again? I see my friends separate to continents around the world, seas rolling between. And on the waves, fear is my sailor. Come blind my heart to the water&rsquo;s edge, die while sobbing on the mainland. The last words I&rsquo;ll speak aren&rsquo;t enough.</p><p>I want to tell my mother and father I&rsquo;m sorry I don&rsquo;t look like the young boy they created. I recall each November shaded with that pale feeling. To set my eyes up and away, to our names crested on dead stars gazing back. I see myself there: some affluent neighborhood resting on wood and water, born again on the sidewalks with my brother Andrew and my dog Monster, raising our laughter over our parents&rsquo; heartbreak. Every cul de sac was tethered together only by the echos of our stomping feet. The songs we liked were the ones we could scream to, melodies booming like torrents from our lungs. We roused hatred from our veins when the sky fell, melting into water too.</p><p>Disenchantment. Maybe that&rsquo;s what this feeling is. And a little self-imprisonment. I remember humming in my bed while my parents screamed at each other from the next room. I couldn&rsquo;t hear my own thoughts. And a whitewashed ceiling combed over. And a whitewashed ceiling combed over again. And I made a wish to fall deeply in love or die trying.</p><p>So the heart does grow forests out of cinder: to burn it down again. As the years go, I feel a dull light pierce through my mind&rsquo;s shallow graveyard. Rekindling. It&rsquo;s forever and always.</p><p>I love my hands for the way they remember. I love my eyes for the way they dream. And I love my darkness for the way it returns, to teach me goodness again. These things were developed by my own soul. Hope&ndash; my earnest defense against the rotation of the sun. Let it curl over me like salt over the brine.</p>
						
						<div class="postmeta"><a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/148454299422/salt-over-the-brine">4 months ago</a>&nbsp; <a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/148454299422/salt-over-the-brine" style="text-transform:lowercase;">Notes (9)</a></div>

