                    <div class="text post">
	
                        
                            <h2>Chamber</h2>
                        

                        <p>At the Wyandanch train station, there is a timid yellow that rides the platform into the distance. One moment you see it, another you don&rsquo;t. It feels like that thing inside of you&ndash; when you&rsquo;re crying, and you&rsquo;re crying with such vigor, that you hear yourself making the most obnoxious of noises, and rising independently from your soul is a sort of self-acknowledgement: <i>The tears are spilling from my eyes now. They will end soon, but for now, I am crying. </i>How dare the mind have such an obvious way out? I wonder&ndash; but for now the train&rsquo;s voice is a falling mountain on all our heads. The echo of our lives. Every tree on Long Island shakes towards the sea, wants to love, wants to feel love. I drove past these tracks for years and happily culled the apathy from my gardened mind, resting it at the forefront of my face so I may greet Manhattan anew. And each time I was afraid of change. I think I&rsquo;ve always been that way.</p><p>Tomorrow I&rsquo;ll be back with my new love beside me. Can Deer Park rest with us inside its chamber, like lightning bugs in a divine heat? I want dry air and thick sun rays, and the Long Island Railroad&rsquo;s captivating roar. I want Robert Moses Beach to comb its salt over suburban roofs, passing us on my porch. A half-dream of tears, waking up to our real lives, to the tiny hairs on our arms touching, to the scent of Sunday in my high school bedroom, retreating from slow sorrow to the youth before our eyes. We can go here: where I laughed my sadness off in the pine barren of an island, clinging tight to the mainland, while my body cried&nbsp;<i>please don&rsquo;t leave me</i>, and still, and yet, finding my spirit awash in the Atlantic. There is no cradle for the now. Just a timid yellow that spills over, reminding. And oh&ndash; I am alive. We&rsquo;ll go see my home, and then we&rsquo;ll go home together.</p>
						
						<div class="postmeta"><a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/147708037252/chamber">4 months ago</a>&nbsp; <a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/147708037252/chamber" style="text-transform:lowercase;">Notes (5)</a></div>

                    </div>
					
					

                


				
                   

			
	
				
				
                
				
				


 				   
                
                
				
                

				
                
                    
                

					<div class="permalink">
						<a href="http://thenatureofdaylight.tumblr.com/post/147459430432/eight-secrets-to-whisper-to-myself">&rarr;</a>
						
					</div>
					
                    <div class="text post">
	
                        
                            <h2>Eight Secrets to Whisper to Myself</h2>
                        

                        <ol><li>I know that every leaf owns its own prints. My bones are creaking at the thought.</li><li>Death waits inside me, and I am enriched by her prayer. This is not acid in my chest. This is my soul reaching out, burning.<br></li><li>The words that come to me when I&rsquo;m alone are not so terribly different from when I&rsquo;m surrounded. They are just louder.</li><li>Maybe 23 years under a blue sky has made me restless. I know my name isn&rsquo;t a cardboard box I must squeeze inside.<br></li><li>Sometime last year, I became acquainted with a quiet feeling. It&rsquo;s been scrubbed till raw, bloodied, and unable to sleep. Unanswered for its whole life. I fell in lust with this feeling, a pure voice that wonders its role. I&rsquo;ll show it to the girl I love. I&rsquo;ll take it and carry it to caves and beaches, night drives and dances. I&rsquo;ll take it to blacktops in the summer. I&rsquo;ll take it with me to my bed&ndash; the quietest feeling in the world.</li><li>Some say the story feels the same everyday. A long time under the same stars. But last night, I floated with the sound of my own voice as it carried Delana into sleep.&nbsp;&ldquo;What do you see when you close your eyes?&rdquo; She told me, <i>hearts</i>. I imagined them beating furiously through black shadow, thumping through the dark sheet of her vision. I imagined her life is like mine. Waiting and willing, holding, terrified, and filled with eager silence. The story feels similar everyday, just enough to keep us hopeful for tomorrow. But sometimes Delana and I sleep in the same place. Sometimes we feel the weight slide. Sometimes we don&rsquo;t carry our identities to bed, and it&rsquo;s beautiful&ndash;with her hair scattered about like stardust through space.</li><li>I was born at the end of August 1993 with a birthmark on my arm about the size of a strawberry. It has since faded away, but I linger, perhaps to recreate proof of my birth outside my body. There is so much contradiction here. So it is love. It is love, I&rsquo;ve decided, which must be the only thing I&rsquo;ve ever known. I will love to prove I exist.</li><li>Summer is here. The highways are long and liquored with light, winding through mountains and valleys. I will feel teenage life call from the bedrock of my blood. I don&rsquo;t want to waste this all&ndash; not tonight.</li></ol>
						
